'''Minimum wage in Croatia''' is regulated by the Minimum Wage Act ({{lang-hr|Zakon o minimalnoj plaći}}) and is defined as the lowest gross monthly wage for a [[full-time]] worker, based on a 40-hour work week.{{sfn|Minimum Wage Act|loc=§2}}{{sfn|Bejaković|2015|p=24}} For workers who do not work full time, minimum wage is lower, in proportion to their [[working time|working hours]].{{sfn|Minimum Wage Act|loc=§2}} Additional compensation for [[overtime]] work, night work, and work on Sundays and holidays is not included in the minimum wage.{{sfn|Minimum Wage Act|loc=§2}} Minimum wage is recalculated once a year and is effective throughout the next calendar year.{{sfn|Minimum Wage Act|loc=§4}}
As of 1 January 2018, the minimum gross monthly wage in Croatia is 3,439 [[Croatian kuna|HRK]] (c.&nbsp;€460), which is equivalent to a net amount of 2,752 HRK (c.&nbsp;€370), or 43% of average monthly wage.<ref name="HRT"/> In January 2018, minimum wage was received by 45,245 workers,<ref name="VL"/> down from c.&nbsp;80,000 in 2014.<ref name="JL"/>
==See also== * [[List of minimum wages by country]] * [[List of European Union member states by minimum wage]]
