'''One (Written) Language''' ({{lang-no|Ett (skrift)språk}}) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[political party]] that ran for the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2009|parliamentary election in 2009]]. The party's main goal is to abolish [[Nynorsk]] as a written language in schools and the public sector.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogg.nrk.no/valgbar/archives/2009/09/sma-og-rare-partier-ett-skrift-sprak.html |title=Små og rare partier: Ett (skrift) språk. |work=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=15 September 2009 |language=Norwegian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110721153211/http://blogg.nrk.no/valgbar/archives/2009/09/sma-og-rare-partier-ett-skrift-sprak.html |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> In 2009, it ran for election in [[Akershus]], and received 100 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/krd/html/valg2009/bs5.html|title=Valg 2009 Landsoversikt - Stortingsvalget|publisher=regjeringen.no ([[Norwegian Ministry of Local Government and Regional Development]])|language=Norwegian|accessdate=15 September 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926023445/http://www.regjeringen.no/krd/html/valg2009/bs5.html|archivedate=26 September 2009|df=}}</ref>
The party was founded by [[Norwegian language]] teacher Einar Smørdal who had previously proposed such a party in a letter to the local newspaper ''[[Møre (newspaper)|Møre]]'' in [[Volda]]. The party's immediate issue was to end compulsory education in Nynorsk in grade and high school, while making [[Bokmål]] the sole language in public documents was a more long-term goal. The party emphasized that it did not oppose spoken dialects, it was having two parallel written languages which they opposed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rb.no/Innenriks/Politikk/article4238556.ece|title=Starter parti mot nynorsk|last=Lier|first=Lars|date=April 2, 2009|publisher=Romerikes Blad|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2009-09-15}}</ref>
