{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox UN resolution |number = 1209 |organ = SC |date = 19 November |year = 1998 |meeting = 3,945 |code = S/RES/1209 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/1209(1998) |for = 15 |abstention = 0 |against = 0 |subject = The situation in Africa |result = Adopted |image = Gun pyre in Uhuru Gardens, Nairobi.jpg |caption = Seized weapons in Kenya }}
'''United Nations Security Council resolution 1209''', adopted unanimously on 19 November 1998, after recalling resolutions [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1170|1170]] (1998) and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1196|1196]] (1998) on Africa, the Council addressed illicit arms flows on the continent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Security Council, acting on Secretary-General's Africa report, adopts texts of status and treatment of refugees, illicit arms flow|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/1998/19981119.sc6598.html|date=19 November 1998|publisher=United Nations}}</ref>
==Observations== The Security Council considered further a report by the Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]] on the situation in Africa concerning the importance of stemming illegal arms flows.<ref>{{cite web|last=Annan|first=Kofi|title=Report of the Secretary-General on the situation in Africa|url=https://undocs.org/S/1998/318|publisher=United Nations|date=13 April 1998}}</ref> It recognised that illegal arms traffic was closely connected to the role of commercial and political interests. African countries did had the right to obtain weapons for reasons of [[national security]] and policing. [[Switzerland]] had offered to hold a conference in [[Geneva]] on illegal arms traffic and there were negotiations in [[Vienna]] on the elaboration of an international convention against transnational organised crime, including a protocol to combat illicit manufacturing and trafficking in [[firearm]]s. The Council commended African initiatives to address the problem of arms flows, uch as in [[Mali]] and [[Mozambique]], the [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS) and the [[Southern African Development Community]] (SADC).
==Acts== The Security Council was concerned about large-scale illegal arms trafficking in Africa, particularly of [[small arms]] and the threat it posed to security, development and humanitarian situation on the continent.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Metz|first=Stephen|title=A Strategic Approach to African Security: Challenges and Prospects|journal=African Security Review|year=2000|volume=9|issue=3}}</ref> In this regard, African countries were urged to introduce legislation on the use of arms. Member States, particularly those that manufactured [[weapon]]s, were reminded of the importance of restricting arms transfers which could provoke or prolong armed conflicts.<ref>{{cite book|last=CQ Press|title=Historic Documents of 1998|year=1999|publisher=CQ Press|isbn=978-1-56802-442-4|page=223}}</ref> The resolution encouraged African states to participate in the United Nations Register of Conventional Arms and to establish regional and subregional registers to enhance the transparency of arms transfers. They were also instructed to look to the [[European Union]] and [[Organization of American States]] for their efforts in tackling the arms trade and to adopt similar measures.
In addition, the Secretary-General was encouraged to find ways to identify international arms dealers acting in contravention of national legislation or [[arms embargo]]es imposed by the United Nations. He was also urged to promote co-operation among Member States, to explore ways of disseminating information on arms flows and their destabilising effects and to implement voluntary weapons collection programmes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brzoska|first=Michael|title=Smart sanctions: the next steps: the debate on arms embargoes and travel sanctions within the 'Bonn-Berlin process'|year=2001|publisher=Nomos|isbn=978-3-7890-7546-9|page=73}}</ref>
